---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const title = 'Articles - Bug Hunter Tools';
const description = 'Complete collection of bug bounty hunting guides, security tool reviews,';
const html = `<article>
            <h1>All Bug Bounty Guides & Articles</h1>
            
            <p>Comprehensive guides, tool reviews, and practical tutorials for bug bounty hunters at all skill levels.</p>

            <section style="margin-top: 40px;">
                <h2>🔥 Breaking Security News</h2>

                <div class="tool">
                    <h3>📋 <a href="/articles/security-roundup-2026-02-17/">Security Roundup Feb 10–16 2026: AI Infrastructure Under Fire, Cloud Misconfigs &amp; $4.3M in Bug Bounties</a></h3>
                    <div class="meta">
                        <span>Published: February 17, 2026</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>~2,600 words</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>12 min read</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span style="color: #667eea; font-weight: bold;">📋 WEEKLY ROUNDUP</span>
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>The week AI infrastructure became the primary attack target.</strong> CVE-2026-22778 (vLLM CVSS 9.8), six n8n CVEs, Azure Functions info disclosure, a real-world 10-minute AWS cloud breach, HackerOne's $4.3M Live Hacking week, and the five patterns defining 2026 security.</p>

                    <p><strong>What you'll learn:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>vLLM &amp; n8n critical CVEs — what to test and how to report responsibly</li>
                        <li>Azure Functions credential exposure patterns (CVE-2026-21532)</li>
                        <li>Real AWS breach: 10 minutes from leaked IAM creds to 19 compromised principals</li>
                        <li>Django ASGI DoS, Chrome SOP bypass, SAP API exposure</li>
                        <li>HackerOne $4.3M payout + Bugcrowd AI triage + Chime double bounties</li>
                        <li>5 essential tools + 4 must-read books with affiliate links</li>
                    </ul>

                    <div class="cta">
                        <a href="/articles/security-roundup-2026-02-17/" class="button">Read Weekly Roundup →</a>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="tool">
                    <h3>🚨 <a href="/articles/vscode-extensions-cve-2025-65717.html">VS Code Extensions Vulnerabilities: 125 Million Developers At Risk — Three CVEs Still Unpatched</a></h3>
                    <div class="meta">
                        <span>Published: February 19, 2026</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>~3,500 words</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>10 min read</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span style="color: #f44336; font-weight: bold;">🚨 BREAKING — THREE UNPATCHED CVEs</span>
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Four critical vulnerabilities in Live Server, Markdown Preview Enhanced, Code Runner, and Microsoft Live Preview affect 125M+ installs.</strong> CVE-2025-65717 (CVSS 9.1) lets any malicious website silently exfiltrate your local files while Live Server is running. Three CVEs remain unpatched with no response from maintainers.</p>

                    <p><strong>What you'll learn:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>CVE-2025-65717: How Live Server exposes your project files to any website you visit</li>
                        <li>CVE-2025-65716: Arbitrary JS execution via crafted markdown files</li>
                        <li>CVE-2025-65715: RCE via poisoned .vscode/settings.json</li>
                        <li>Real-world attack scenarios for each vulnerability</li>
                        <li>Immediate mitigations and long-term hardening steps</li>
                        <li>What this means for developer-environment bug bounty hunting</li>
                    </ul>

                    <div class="cta">
                        <a href="/articles/vscode-extensions-cve-2025-65717.html" class="button" style="background: #f44336;">🔥 Read Critical Analysis →</a>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="tool">
                    <h3>🚨 <a href="/articles/n8n-rce-cve-2026-25049.html">Critical n8n Vulnerability: Six CVEs Expose Workflow Automation to RCE</a></h3>
                    <div class="meta">
                        <span>Published: February 11, 2026</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>5,900 words</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>9 min read</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span style="color: #f44336; font-weight: bold;">CRITICAL - CVSS 9.4</span>
                    </div>
                    
                    <p><strong>Six critical vulnerabilities in one day. CVE-2026-25049 scores 9.4 CVSS. Type confusion sandbox escape enables RCE.</strong> n8n workflow automation hit with devastating security disclosure affecting thousands of deployments.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>What you'll learn:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>CVE-2026-25049: Type confusion sandbox escape exploitation</li>
                        <li>JavaScript sandbox bypass techniques (prototype pollution)</li>
                        <li>Five additional CVEs: XSS, auth bypass, path traversal, SQLi, SSTI</li>
                        <li>Credential theft and cloud infrastructure compromise</li>
                        <li>Detection strategies and remediation steps</li>
                        <li>Upgrade to 1.123.17+ or 2.5.2+ immediately</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <div class="cta">
                        <a href="/articles/n8n-rce-cve-2026-25049.html" class="button" style="background: #f44336;">🔥 Read Critical Analysis →</a>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="tool">
                    <h3>🚨 <a href="/articles/n8n-rce-cve-2026-21858.html">Critical n8n Vulnerability: CVSS 10.0 RCE Threatens Cloud Workflow Platforms</a></h3>

                    <div class="meta">
                        <span>Published: February 8, 2026</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>5,400 words</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>8 min read</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span style="color: #f44336; font-weight: bold;">CRITICAL - CVSS 10.0</span>
                    </div>
                    
                    <p><strong>Perfect CVSS 10.0 score. Unauthenticated RCE. Complete server takeover.</strong> CVE-2026-21858 in n8n workflow automation platform is one of the most critical cloud vulnerabilities of 2026.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>What you'll learn:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Content-type confusion vulnerability exploitation in webhooks</li>
                        <li>Attack chain: Arbitrary file read → Session forgery → RCE</li>
                        <li>How to test for content-type confusion in APIs</li>
                        <li>Cloud infrastructure lateral movement scenarios (AWS/Azure/GCP)</li>
                        <li>Immediate mitigation steps for n8n users</li>
                        <li>Why this pattern matters for bug bounty hunters</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <div class="cta">
                        <a href="/articles/n8n-rce-cve-2026-21858.html" class="button" style="background: #f44336;">🔥 Read Critical Analysis →</a>
    <article class="article-card">
        <h2><a href="/articles/vllm-rce-cve-2026-22778.html">CVE-2026-22778: Critical vLLM RCE Vulnerability Threatens AI Infrastructure</a></h2>
        <p class="meta">February 10, 2026 • 🚨 BREAKING - CVSS 9.8 CRITICAL</p>
        <p>Critical remote code execution vulnerability in vLLM LLM serving framework. Default installations vulnerable to unauthenticated RCE affecting GPU clusters.</p>
    </article>

                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="tool">
                    <h3>🚨 <a href="/articles/chainlit-ai-vulnerabilities-cve-2026-22218.html">ChainLeak: AI Framework Vulnerabilities Enable Enterprise Cloud Takeovers</a></h3>
                    <div class="meta">
                        <span>Published: February 8, 2026</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>4,800 words</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>7 min read</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span style="color: #f44336; font-weight: bold;">BREAKING NEWS</span>
                    </div>
                    
                    <p><strong>Critical CVE-2026-22218 and CVE-2026-22219 vulnerabilities discovered in Chainlit AI framework enable cloud takeovers.</strong> Arbitrary file read and SSRF vulnerabilities allow attackers to steal AWS credentials and access enterprise infrastructure.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>What you'll learn:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>How ChainLeak enables AWS cloud takeover in under 10 minutes</li>
                        <li>Arbitrary file read exploitation (CVE-2026-22218)</li>
                        <li>SSRF to AWS IMDS credential theft (CVE-2026-22219)</li>
                        <li>Testing AI frameworks for security vulnerabilities</li>
                        <li>Snort/WAF detection rules for ChainLeak</li>
                        <li>Cloud hardening: IMDSv2, least privilege IAM, network segmentation</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <div class="cta">
                        <a href="/articles/chainlit-ai-vulnerabilities-cve-2026-22218.html" class="button">Read Full Analysis →</a>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="tool">
                    <h3>🚨 <a href="/articles/linkedin-api-bola-bypass.html">LinkedIn API Access Control Bypass - BOLA Testing Guide</a></h3>
                    <div class="meta">
                        <span>Published: February 8, 2026</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>3,200 words</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>6 min read</span>
                    </div>
                    
                    <p><strong>Two major access control bugs just disclosed on LinkedIn's HackerOne program.</strong> Learn how to find BOLA/IDOR vulnerabilities in GraphQL APIs and premium feature bypasses.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>What you'll learn:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>How LinkedIn's comment permission bypass worked</li>
                        <li>Premium feature access via GraphQL manipulation</li>
                        <li>Step-by-step BOLA testing methodology</li>
                        <li>GraphQL-specific testing techniques</li>
                        <li>Essential tools (Burp Suite, Postman, Autorize)</li>
                        <li>Bounty ranges for BOLA bugs ($500-10,000)</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <div class="cta">
                        <a href="/articles/linkedin-api-bola-bypass.html" class="button">Read Analysis →</a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>Getting Started</h2>
                
                <div class="tool">
                    <h3>🎯 <a href="/articles/bug-bounty-starter-kit.html">Bug Bounty Starter Kit 2026</a></h3>
                    <div class="meta">
                        <span>Published: February 8, 2026</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>5,500 words</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>12 min read</span>
                    </div>
                    
                    <p>Complete shopping list for beginners with three budget levels ($100, $500, $1,000+). Includes exact product recommendations, priority purchase order, ROI timelines, and realistic first-year earnings projections.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>Topics covered:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Essential books (priority reading order)</li>
                        <li>Hardware requirements (WiFi adapters, Raspberry Pi, YubiKey)</li>
                        <li>Software subscriptions (when to invest)</li>
                        <li>Home lab setup guide</li>
                        <li>ROI analysis (when tools pay for themselves)</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <div class="cta">
                        <a href="/articles/bug-bounty-starter-kit.html" class="button">Read Full Guide →</a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>Security Tools & Reviews</h2>
                
                <div class="tool">
                    <h3>🔧 <a href="/articles/security-testing-tools-2026.html">Best Security Testing Tools for Bug Bounty Hunters 2026</a></h3>
                    <div class="meta">
                        <span>Published: February 8, 2026</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>3,000 words</span>
                        <span>•</span>
                        <span>15 min read</span>
                    </div>
                    
                    <p>Comprehensive review of the 12 essential security testing tools every bug bounty hunter needs. Covers web application scanners, API testing tools, reconnaissance platforms, and automation frameworks.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>Tools reviewed:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Burp Suite Professional vs OWASP ZAP</li>
                        <li>Nuclei (7,000+ vulnerability templates)</li>
                        <li>ProjectDiscovery Suite (Subfinder, Httpx, Katana)</li>
                        <li>Postman & GraphQL tools</li>
                        <li>Shodan for reconnaissance</li>
                        <li>Cloud security tools (ScoutSuite, Prowler)</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <div class="cta">
                        <a href="/" class="button">Read Full Review →</a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>Coming Soon</h2>
                
                <div style="background: #f8f9fa; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #667eea;">
                    <p><strong>New guides published weekly:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Best WiFi Adapters for Penetration Testing 2026</li>
                        <li>Building a Home Penetration Testing Lab</li>
                        <li>Security Certifications Worth Getting (CEH, OSCP, Security+)</li>
                        <li>Best Security Books for Bug Bounty Hunters</li>
                        <li>Free vs Paid Security Tools - What's Worth Buying?</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Subscribe below to get notified when new guides are published!</strong></p>
                </div>
            </section>

        </article>`;
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <Fragment set:html={html} />
</BaseLayout>
